00:26:11,744 --> 00:26:16,174
[SPEAKER_07]: I have made it absolutely clear to everybody that under no circumstances will that happen.

334
00:26:16,254 --> 00:26:27,297
[SPEAKER_07]: The biggest privatisation of the NHS, of course, took place under the last Labour government, which put in the ruinous PFI

335
00:26:27,277 --> 00:26:36,696
[SPEAKER_07]: I have gone round many hospitals talking to fantastic staff and management there who are bearing the burden of that debt.

336
00:26:36,716 --> 00:26:38,119
[SPEAKER_07]: We will now have to deal with it.

337
00:26:38,219 --> 00:26:42,788
[SPEAKER_08]: Your party opposed the formation of the NHS in the first place.

338
00:26:42,768 --> 00:27:05,130
[SPEAKER_08]: It is factually so, but the more important thing is that your party has presided over cuts in our NHS, increased waiting times and waiting lists, a record number of people delayed in getting appointments and a social care system that is in crisis.

339
00:27:05,110 --> 00:27:09,557
[SPEAKER_07]: There are 17,000 more nurses now than there were under the Labour Party.

340
00:27:09,577 --> 00:27:13,423
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's because we've had a strong economy that's enabled us to make investments.

341
00:27:13,443 --> 00:27:18,431
[SPEAKER_07]: And we are now going to step those investments up, because we believe passionately in the NHS.

342
00:27:18,591 --> 00:27:25,843
[SPEAKER_07]: And the way to take this country forward, the way to get it moving, is to get rid of the blockade in Parliament, get Brexit done, and move on.

343
00:27:25,863 --> 00:27:30,009
[SPEAKER_07]: There are 43,000... Jeremy Corbyn... Let me just ask you, Mr Corbyn...

344
00:27:30,029 --> 00:27:31,712
[SPEAKER_09]: There are 43,000 nurse vacancies.

345
00:27:31,752 --> 00:27:32,353
[SPEAKER_09]: That's the fact.

346
00:27:32,493 --> 00:27:32,974
[SPEAKER_09]: Understood.

347
00:27:32,954 --> 00:27:41,230
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, you sent an email on behalf of the Labour Party saying, imagine opening a five-figure bill for your cancer treatment.

348
00:27:41,791 --> 00:27:43,754
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you accept that that is totally misleading?

349
00:27:43,774 --> 00:27:49,866
[SPEAKER_09]: There is no possibility of anybody having NHS cancer treatment and having to pay a five-figure bill?

350
00:27:49,846 --> 00:27:52,331
[SPEAKER_08]: If you end up with a privatised service, that's what you get.

351
00:27:52,392 --> 00:27:54,837
[SPEAKER_08]: If you end up with that US trade deal, that is what you get.

352
00:27:54,897 --> 00:27:58,084
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, the Prime Minister says he's not going to do that sort of a trade deal.

353
00:27:58,264 --> 00:28:01,351
[SPEAKER_08]: If that's the case, why did the talks go on for two years?

354
00:28:01,632 --> 00:28:06,302
[SPEAKER_08]: It doesn't take two years to say no to privatisation of the NHS.

355
00:28:06,282 --> 00:28:08,105
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, thank you, gentlemen.

356
00:28:08,125 --> 00:28:09,146
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you very much indeed.

357
00:28:09,186 --> 00:28:10,208
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you very much indeed.

358
00:28:10,228 --> 00:28:12,050
[SPEAKER_09]: We've got lots and lots of questions to get through.

359
00:28:12,070 --> 00:28:13,272
[SPEAKER_09]: I want to give you the chance to move on.

360
00:28:13,573 --> 00:28:17,518
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, because we've had lots of questions, one or two we're going to make rather quicker than the rest.

361
00:28:17,538 --> 00:28:19,281
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll come to one of those in just a second.

362
00:28:19,301 --> 00:28:21,204
[SPEAKER_09]: You can join in this debate, of course.

363
00:28:21,524 --> 00:28:25,450
[SPEAKER_09]: Hashtag BBC debate on social media.

364
00:28:25,750 --> 00:28:35,985
[SPEAKER_09]: And before we return to one of our longer questions, we've got an interesting question here from Phil Wason, who has written in, can't be here tonight, which has the better track record

365
00:28:35,965 --> 00:28:42,412
[SPEAKER_09]: of raising the living standards of the poor, socialism or capitalism?

366
00:28:42,912 --> 00:28:44,033
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy Corbyn.

367
00:28:44,053 --> 00:28:53,543
[SPEAKER_08]: Socialism carried out in a democratic way in this country, in Scandinavia and other places, has raised the living standards of the very poorest.

368
00:28:53,663 --> 00:29:00,851
[SPEAKER_08]: And it was the post-war Labour government that did massively to improve the living standards of the poorest working-class communities in this country.

369
00:29:01,131 --> 00:29:04,234
[SPEAKER_08]: And our Labour government will do the same again.

370
00:29:04,636 --> 00:29:20,823
[SPEAKER_07]: And I would say that it is one nation conservatism which understands the vital importance of a dynamic market economy as the only way in which you can pay for fantastic public services and for looking after the poorest and neediest in our society.

371
00:29:21,043 --> 00:29:25,851
[SPEAKER_07]: That is the balance and symmetry at the heart of what I'm trying to achieve with this government.

372
00:29:25,831 --> 00:29:32,759
[SPEAKER_07]: and I think that to attack capitalism, as Mr Corbyn and Mr Macdonald do, is absolutely senseless.

373
00:29:32,779 --> 00:29:42,569
[SPEAKER_07]: And by the way, to continue to attack all free trade is, I also think, ignorant of the fact... Just to be clear, Mr Johnson, you think he wants to destroy capitalism?

374
00:29:42,609 --> 00:29:43,410
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that your view?

375
00:29:43,430 --> 00:29:50,758
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, John Macdonald, who is the Shadow Chancellor, and some would say the intellectual driving force behind...

376
00:29:50,738 --> 00:29:58,431
[SPEAKER_07]: this type of polio socialism is committed, he says, to fomenting the overthrow of capitalism.

377
00:29:58,451 --> 00:30:00,394
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that is a mistake.

378
00:30:00,695 --> 00:30:02,478
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think that's the right way forward for our country.

379
00:30:02,738 --> 00:30:04,681
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe in supporting businesses.

380
00:30:04,942 --> 00:30:06,525
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe in cutting... Let him respond.

381
00:30:06,705 --> 00:30:09,810
[SPEAKER_08]: My kind of socialism is one where you don't leave people behind.

382
00:30:09,790 --> 00:30:13,335
[SPEAKER_08]: You don't ignore the fact that four million of our children are living in poverty.

383
00:30:13,576 --> 00:30:19,324
[SPEAKER_08]: You don't ignore the fact that there are thousands of people sleeping on the streets of this country, the fifth richest country in the world.

384
00:30:19,564 --> 00:30:21,467
[SPEAKER_08]: The inequality has got worse.

385
00:30:21,487 --> 00:30:25,333
[SPEAKER_08]: 150 billionaires in Britain, more people poor than ever.

386
00:30:25,413 --> 00:30:26,074
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy Corbyn, thank you.

387
00:30:26,094 --> 00:30:26,595
[SPEAKER_09]: That cannot be right.

388
00:30:26,835 --> 00:30:28,838
[SPEAKER_09]: We're going to turn on to a broader question.

389
00:30:29,859 --> 00:30:35,027
[SPEAKER_09]: We're moving on to a broader question about the economy, so both of the leaders will have the chance to talk at greater length.

390
00:30:35,187 --> 00:30:37,611
[SPEAKER_09]: Andrew Brooke has our next question.

391
00:30:37,651 --> 00:30:38,532
[SPEAKER_09]: Andrew Brooke, please.

392
00:30:38,832 --> 00:30:39,172
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

393
00:30:40,334 --> 00:30:47,924
[SPEAKER_05]: Both of you say that if you're asked to form a government next week, you will spend, spend, spend, making your plans, your expenditure plans, that is, seem like a fantasy.

394
00:30:48,565 --> 00:30:53,271
[SPEAKER_05]: How are we really going to pay for everything that you are promising?

395
00:30:53,631 --> 00:30:55,093
[SPEAKER_09]: Andrew Brock, thank you very much indeed.

396
00:30:55,554 --> 00:30:58,458
[SPEAKER_09]: Spend, spend, spend, he says you're both going to do, gentlemen.

397
00:30:58,478 --> 00:31:01,161
[SPEAKER_09]: He wants to know how both of you are going to pay

398
00:31:01,141 --> 00:31:03,304
[SPEAKER_09]: or rather how we're going to pay for your plans.

399
00:31:03,365 --> 00:31:04,406
[SPEAKER_07]: Boris Johnson.

400
00:31:04,426 --> 00:31:05,548
[SPEAKER_07]: Andrew, thank you very much.

401
00:31:05,568 --> 00:31:15,524
[SPEAKER_07]: And we will certainly be making some big investments in, as I say, in the NHS, in putting more police on the streets, in lifting up our education funding for every school in the country.

402
00:31:15,544 --> 00:31:16,365
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to continue with that.

403
00:31:16,766 --> 00:31:22,315
[SPEAKER_07]: But what we won't do is borrow hugely to fund day-to-day investment.

404
00:31:22,655 --> 00:31:25,480
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is the mistake that the Labour Party would make.

405
00:31:25,700 --> 00:31:26,862
[SPEAKER_07]: They would rack up

406
00:31:26,842 --> 00:31:32,009
[SPEAKER_07]: are debts, they would put up spending to 1.2 trillion.

407
00:31:32,029 --> 00:31:38,278
[SPEAKER_07]: To answer your question, what that would mean is a tax burden of £2,400 per taxpayer.

408
00:31:38,519 --> 00:31:41,804
[SPEAKER_07]: You hear from Labour sometimes that the burden is...

409
00:31:41,824 --> 00:31:47,171
[SPEAKER_07]: I think Mr Corbyn said it just now, the burden is going to fall only on the 150 billionaires or the top 5%.

410
00:31:47,792 --> 00:31:55,363
[SPEAKER_07]: Actually, people on as little as £20,000 a year under their plans will be paying £1,000 a year more in tax.

411
00:31:55,343 --> 00:31:58,589
[SPEAKER_09]: Jeremy Corbyn, he says the people who are not rich will pay for your plans.

412
00:31:58,609 --> 00:32:07,624
[SPEAKER_08]: We're very clear about that and we are the only party that's produced a fully costed manifesto with a grey book that adds up to every piece of expenditure we want.

413
00:32:08,045 --> 00:32:12,272
[SPEAKER_08]: The problem with this country is we've gone too far down the road.

414
00:32:12,252 --> 00:32:13,454
[SPEAKER_08]: of free market economics.

415
00:32:13,574 --> 00:32:15,557
[SPEAKER_08]: We've created too much inequality.

416
00:32:16,018 --> 00:32:24,672
[SPEAKER_08]: And if every single bit of our manifesto was carried out tomorrow, we would just about reach the level of the public services of France or Germany.

417
00:32:24,952 --> 00:32:26,435
[SPEAKER_08]: That is how far backwards we've gone.

418
00:32:26,735 --> 00:32:29,620
[SPEAKER_08]: There has to be investment in our schools.

419
00:32:29,600 --> 00:32:32,003
[SPEAKER_08]: Why are so many children in oversized classes?

420
00:32:32,364 --> 00:32:38,312
[SPEAKER_08]: Why are so many children growing up in insecure housing because there isn't the sufficiency of council housing available?

421
00:32:38,592 --> 00:32:40,615
[SPEAKER_08]: Why are there so many people waiting for social care?

422
00:32:40,815 --> 00:32:48,867
[SPEAKER_08]: Why do so many people in middle age have to go into debt to pay for their kids to go through university and the social care that their older parents need?

423
00:32:49,107 --> 00:32:52,251
[SPEAKER_08]: It's simply time to invest in our future.

424
00:32:52,291 --> 00:32:54,835
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Boris Johnson.

425
00:32:54,855 --> 00:32:55,776
[SPEAKER_07]: And I agree.

426
00:32:55,756 --> 00:33:19,449
[SPEAKER_07]: and I agree, but the difference between Mr Corbyn and myself is that his plans, and as I say, we will be making substantial investments within the fiscal headroom that we have, but whilst bearing down on our debt over the life of the Parliament, but what we won't do is rack up such debts that the markets demand a higher interest rate and you end up with huge tax burdens falling on everybody else.

427
00:33:19,709 --> 00:33:23,795
[SPEAKER_07]: Labour always ends their time in office with an economic crisis.

428
00:33:24,336 --> 00:33:25,257
[SPEAKER_07]: Corbyn and McDonnell

429
00:33:25,237 --> 00:33:29,645
[SPEAKER_07]: Corbyn and McDonnell would start their time in office with an economic crisis.

430
00:33:29,785 --> 00:33:34,153
[SPEAKER_09]: Mr Corbyn, he says that all of us will pay more in our taxes, not just the rich.

431
00:33:34,714 --> 00:33:37,720
[SPEAKER_09]: And independent think tanks like the Institute of Fiscal Studies agree.

432
00:33:37,760 --> 00:33:38,401
[SPEAKER_09]: That's what they say.

433
00:33:38,421 --> 00:33:40,765
[SPEAKER_08]: They don't agree with that point, actually.

434
00:33:40,745 --> 00:33:45,551
[SPEAKER_09]: Clearly not true, they said, of your claim that only the top 5% of earners would pay more.

435
00:33:45,571 --> 00:33:50,357
[SPEAKER_08]: They questioned some aspects of our programme, and we're happy to discuss that with them.

436
00:33:50,377 --> 00:33:53,601
[SPEAKER_08]: But we are the party that actually produced the funding of it.

437
00:33:53,621 --> 00:34:00,709
[SPEAKER_08]: The Conservative Party have produced nothing in the way of how they're going to pay for anything they suggest they're doing, other than tax cuts.

438
00:34:00,769 --> 00:34:06,456
[SPEAKER_08]: It's very hard to see how you can expand services if you're cutting the income base of government in the first place.

439
00:34:06,637 --> 00:34:07,798
[SPEAKER_08]: It's a fair question, isn't it?

440
00:34:07,778 --> 00:34:11,582
[SPEAKER_08]: There has to be investment to deal with the inequalities within our society.

441
00:34:11,602 --> 00:34:14,545
[SPEAKER_07]: How do you pretend to cut taxes and pay for more, Mr Johnson?

442
00:34:14,685 --> 00:34:17,367
[SPEAKER_07]: Because Labour didn't produce the funding for anything.

443
00:34:17,808 --> 00:34:29,239
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm afraid it's the hard work of the British people and it's British companies, it's British businesses, large and small, that produce the funding that pays for our National Health Service and everything else.

444
00:34:29,299 --> 00:34:35,085
[SPEAKER_07]: And we're a government that understands that if you're going to have a dynamic market economy, you cannot clobber them.

445
00:34:35,065 --> 00:34:41,474
[SPEAKER_07]: You cannot clobber companies with the highest taxes in Europe, which is what Mr Corbyn and the Labour Party would do.

446
00:34:41,915 --> 00:34:46,681
[SPEAKER_07]: It would be entirely wrong for this country to go down the route that they are proposing.

447
00:34:46,842 --> 00:34:48,864
[SPEAKER_07]: I quoted the IFS ad, Mr Corbyn.

448
00:34:48,884 --> 00:34:49,706
[SPEAKER_09]: Let me quote them at you.

449
00:34:49,726 --> 00:34:57,096
[SPEAKER_09]: He says, your prospectus, say the Institute of Fiscal Studies, top economic think tank, your prospectus, they say, is not credible.

450
00:34:57,456 --> 00:35:00,961
[SPEAKER_09]: They say, you haven't said how you'll pay for social care, you haven't said how you'll pay for future tax.

451
00:35:00,981 --> 00:35:02,203
[SPEAKER_09]: That's not credible, they say.

452
00:35:02,183 --> 00:35:09,032
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, on the contrary, our programme is fully costed, it's there in the manifesto, and it's a great, great programme.

453
00:35:09,052 --> 00:35:25,272
[SPEAKER_07]: And the one other advantage that we have, apart from not wrecking the economy and not having a fiscal meltdown, which is what Labour always do, putting up taxes for everybody, we would get our country moving forwards again by getting Brexit done.

454
00:35:25,493 --> 00:35:27,415
[SPEAKER_07]: And the economic drag anchor

455
00:35:27,395 --> 00:35:31,084
[SPEAKER_07]: of Brexit on this country should not be underestimated.

456
00:35:31,305 --> 00:35:32,728
[SPEAKER_07]: It is stopping investment.

457
00:35:32,748 --> 00:35:37,820
[SPEAKER_07]: It means that people are uncertain about making purchases, about taking on new jobs.

458
00:35:38,141 --> 00:35:42,973
[SPEAKER_08]: What Conservative governments always do is look after the very richest within our society.

459
00:35:42,953 --> 00:35:58,754
[SPEAKER_08]: They've done very, very well in the years of austerity, while it's communities all over the country that have paid for it with closed libraries, closed swimming pools, out of reach pricing on sports facilities, lack of housing, increased stress, increased mental health stress.

460
00:35:58,994 --> 00:36:02,619
[SPEAKER_08]: We have to redress the imbalances within our society.

461
00:36:03,179 --> 00:36:05,923
[SPEAKER_08]: And our tax proposals

462
00:36:06,460 --> 00:36:19,633
[SPEAKER_08]: for corporation tax would be to raise it to 26% at the end of the first period of that Labour government, which would actually be lower than it was in 2010, lower than it is in France, lower than it is in the USA.

463
00:36:19,953 --> 00:36:27,540
[SPEAKER_08]: What we're proposing is a serious set of plans in order to start addressing the imbalances within our society.

464
00:36:27,580 --> 00:36:28,822
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it's important to do that.

465
00:36:28,922 --> 00:36:34,307
[SPEAKER_09]: His claim is basically that Labour would just bring us into line with many countries around the world and Western Europe.

466
00:36:34,287 --> 00:36:46,428
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it is quite incredible that Mr Corbyn should claim that people on £20,000 a year are amongst the richest in society and therefore deserve to be clobbered by his tax increases.

467
00:36:46,528 --> 00:36:48,191
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that is totally wrong.

468
00:36:48,712 --> 00:36:54,522
[SPEAKER_07]: The burden of taxation always falls most heavily on those on modest and low incomes.

469
00:36:54,542 --> 00:36:57,367
[SPEAKER_07]: That is what will happen if Labour are allowed to get in.

470
00:36:57,447 --> 00:36:57,848
[SPEAKER_07]: If we have

471
00:36:57,828 --> 00:37:01,954
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a Corbyn-Sturgeon coalition.

472
00:37:02,314 --> 00:37:14,591
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm afraid it will lead to an economic disaster and, worse still, it will lead to the political stalemate, the frustration for business that wants to get on, the uncertainty of not knowing what the position on Brexit is.

473
00:37:14,751 --> 00:37:23,564
[SPEAKER_07]: And we still haven't heard from Mr Corbyn, this debate has now been running for 35 minutes, whether he's in favour of the deal that he was about to do and how he would negotiate it.

474
00:37:23,584 --> 00:37:24,645
[SPEAKER_08]: I still don't know.

475
00:37:24,625 --> 00:37:26,687
[SPEAKER_08]: You know what the business organisations tell me is?

476
00:37:27,228 --> 00:37:29,590
[SPEAKER_08]: They can't stand the uncertainty of this government.

477
00:37:29,610 --> 00:37:32,994
[SPEAKER_08]: They can't stand the idea of a no-deal exit.

478
00:37:33,194 --> 00:37:41,682
[SPEAKER_08]: They want to make sure they're able to continue that trade and continue that just-in-time delivery system that is so important in manufacturing industry.

479
00:37:42,043 --> 00:37:52,033
[SPEAKER_08]: And they are constantly concerned at the lack of understanding of how industry works from a Conservative government that claims to be in support of those industries.

480
00:37:52,013 --> 00:38:00,386
[SPEAKER_09]: What he said to you, Mr Corbyn, I want to give you the chance to answer it, is that businesses, even ones that were in favour of Remain, want certainty, they want clarity, they want to get it done.

481
00:38:00,406 --> 00:38:01,450
[SPEAKER_09]: What's your answer to him?

482
00:38:02,088 --> 00:38:07,877
[SPEAKER_08]: With us, you will get a deal which would be leave, but leave with a trade arrangement.

483
00:38:08,197 --> 00:38:12,063
[SPEAKER_08]: Or you get remain, which will obviously carry on the current situation.

484
00:38:12,184 --> 00:38:22,159
[SPEAKER_08]: But they would have the certainty of knowing what the trade relationship is, where the investment is going to come from, and where the market is for the goods that are made in this country.

485
00:38:22,179 --> 00:38:24,062
[SPEAKER_08]: It's kind of important to know those things.

486
00:38:24,042 --> 00:38:25,243
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you very much, gentlemen.

487
00:38:25,263 --> 00:38:25,924
[SPEAKER_08]: Very briefly.

488
00:38:26,184 --> 00:38:27,526
[SPEAKER_07]: Very briefly.

489
00:38:27,546 --> 00:38:37,598
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it is important to know those things, but it's absolutely unclear what that deal would be, what Mr Corbyn proposes to leave, and who in his party proposes to campaign for the deal he's going to do.

490
00:38:37,618 --> 00:38:37,878
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

491
00:38:37,898 --> 00:38:39,780
[SPEAKER_09]: You've made that point very well earlier on.

492
00:38:39,800 --> 00:38:46,088
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's turn to another question now, a very important subject, given the events of recent days, the issue of security.

493
00:38:46,168 --> 00:38:48,470
[SPEAKER_09]: And the question comes from Richard Boustred.

494
00:38:48,530 --> 00:38:49,932
[SPEAKER_09]: Mr Boustred, please.

495
00:38:50,654 --> 00:38:55,542
[SPEAKER_06]: Your most important responsibility, if you become Prime Minister in a week's time, will be to keep us safe.

496
00:38:56,142 --> 00:39:02,052
[SPEAKER_06]: Given the terror attacks we've seen on the streets of London, are you prepared to put public safety ahead of human rights?

497
00:39:02,412 --> 00:39:08,241
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn, will you put public safety ahead of human rights, Mr Basterdas?

498
00:39:08,221 --> 00:39:09,283
[SPEAKER_08]: It is not an either or.

499
00:39:09,644 --> 00:39:24,492
[SPEAKER_08]: You have to keep the public safe, you have to ensure that the police are there and properly funded, you have to ensure the prison system works and is effective, that the parole board works and is effective, that the probation service works and is effective.

500
00:39:24,712 --> 00:39:26,896
[SPEAKER_08]: You have to give people that security.

501
00:39:27,117 --> 00:39:30,203
[SPEAKER_08]: You don't get security on the cheap, you have to invest in it.

502
00:39:30,623 --> 00:39:31,545
[SPEAKER_08]: Human rights

503
00:39:31,525 --> 00:39:37,885
[SPEAKER_08]: are our defence against autocracy and our defence against abuse of power.

504
00:39:37,905 --> 00:39:40,955
[SPEAKER_08]: There is no difference between wanting security and human rights.

505
00:39:40,995 --> 00:39:44,185
[SPEAKER_08]: The two things are actually inextricably linked together.

506
00:39:44,418 --> 00:39:46,802
[SPEAKER_07]: Boris Johnson?

507
00:39:46,822 --> 00:40:05,970
[SPEAKER_07]: I see absolutely no reason to compromise people's human rights, such as the perpetrator of the atrocious killings at London Bridge, but I do think that it was extraordinary and wrong that he should be out on early release and automatic.

508
00:40:05,950 --> 00:40:07,112
[SPEAKER_07]: early release.

509
00:40:07,553 --> 00:40:14,584
[SPEAKER_07]: I said long before I became Prime Minister that we needed to campaign against short sentences.

510
00:40:15,045 --> 00:40:18,831
[SPEAKER_07]: I said in August that we should get rid of automatic early release.

511
00:40:18,871 --> 00:40:25,221
[SPEAKER_07]: I have been very sad to see this guy out on the streets able to do what he did.

512
00:40:25,261 --> 00:40:26,423
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a bill

513
00:40:26,403 --> 00:40:46,066
[SPEAKER_07]: waiting to go, stuck because of the blockade in Parliament, if we can get a working majority, we can get rid of automatic early release and make sure for serious sexual and violent offenders, and make sure that terrorists, people who are convicted of terrorist offences, serve their full sentence.

514
00:40:46,086 --> 00:40:49,069
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that is what this country would expect.

515
00:40:49,049 --> 00:40:53,193
[SPEAKER_09]: What is wrong, Mr Corbyn, with the idea... Just put that point to him and they'll come back to you.

516
00:40:53,413 --> 00:41:00,139
[SPEAKER_09]: What is wrong with the idea that Boris Johnson spells out there that terrorists, particularly terrorists, should serve their full sentence?

517
00:41:00,159 --> 00:41:04,523
[SPEAKER_08]: You have to run a prison system and a judicial system in a proper way.

518
00:41:04,643 --> 00:41:07,206
[SPEAKER_08]: You have to have a prison system that works.

519
00:41:07,926 --> 00:41:11,309
[SPEAKER_08]: One day, pretty well all prisoners are going to come out at some point.

520
00:41:11,690 --> 00:41:16,474
[SPEAKER_08]: But if you don't run a prison system that includes rehabilitation,

521
00:41:16,454 --> 00:41:25,758
[SPEAKER_08]: and you don't have a proper assessment of people before they're given any form of early release and a proper review of those cases, then there's obviously a danger to all of us.

522
00:41:25,878 --> 00:41:29,367
[SPEAKER_08]: And so what happened on the streets of London was utterly appalling.

523
00:41:29,748 --> 00:41:33,197
[SPEAKER_08]: And I was very moved by what

524
00:41:33,312 --> 00:41:45,950
[SPEAKER_08]: Jack Merritt's father said about what his son was trying to do, that he wanted a society where you did address the huge problems where somebody committed awful acts like that.

525
00:41:46,291 --> 00:41:47,933
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, of course, you must imprison them.

526
00:41:47,953 --> 00:41:51,498
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, of course, you must try and rehabilitate them if you can.

527
00:41:51,538 --> 00:41:54,603
[SPEAKER_08]: But there has to be a monitoring process to achieve that.

